snippet.textDisplay: I had that 800W SFX-L power supply, I found it would cut out a lot at random times if under high load ( at around about 740W from the wall or above). I ended up getting another one thinking it was a bad unit(there aren't many options for high power SFX PSUs) but had the same problem with the second one. snippet.textDisplay:
Hi Linus, I'm currently an engineering major I think I know what's going on with your unexpected shutdowns.

Considering that you're using solenoids which are basically inductors, initiating power to a coil creates a magnetic field. And when power is cut, that magnetic field collapses. As a result, you can have voltage spikes that are a few thousand volts but only last for a split second. This phenomenon is called *flyback*. This is actually quite common in DC motors and is why you have to have something called a *flyback diode*, which is as simple as putting a diode across the solenoid. A flyback diode is sort of like a valve that allows the voltage spike to ground itself out instead of back-feeding into the power supply and causing an overvoltage shutdown on the PSU. Hope this helps!
